documented_species.name: Sea Anemone
documented_species.description: At first glance these may look like flowers you'd find in the garden of someone who lives underwater, fearing that some catastrophic event will wipe out all of humanity on land, but they are infact animals. They use their 'foot' to anchor onto a suitable surface. The mouth that they have on the top is surrounded by a mass of tentacles that they use to paralyze their prey before drawing them into their mouths.

documented_species.name: Compass Jellyfish
documented_species.description: These living blobs of gel are a common type of jellyfish, inhabiting shallower waters. The brown streaks on its bell make it look like a compass, hence the name. It is adviced not to touch the tentacles, unless you think it is a good idea to get a rather painful sting.

documented_species.name: Barnacle
documented_species.description: It was long thought that barnacles were mollusks, since they live in shells. It wasn't until 1830 that they were discovered to be crustaceans! Yep, they are more closely related to crabs than limpets and snails. Barnacles start their lives as tiny free living larvae that look unmistakingly like crustaceans. Later on they attach themselves to a surface and form a shell.

documented_species.name: Reef Coral
documented_species.description: Corals are one those things that we tend to treat as a background decoration, like what we do with plants, which is funny given the fact that they are animals, thousands of them infact. A coral is not one, but many many individuals that make up a colony. Each individual is called a polyp, and they look like miniature anemones. Reef corals generally have a calcium carbonate skeleton for structural support and host symbiotic algae that can provide sugars.

documented_species.name: Clownfish
documented_species.description: Clownfish, also known as Anemonefish, are famously known for their bright orange colour and white stripes. They are some of the few creatures able to survive the stinging toxins of sea anemones, allowing them to form a mutualistic symbiotic relationship with them. The fish gains protection under the toxic tentacles, and in return the fish can pick off parasites from the anemone.
